WEBVTT

NOTE Draft captions generated from the narration script. Timing is approximate and should be checked before upload.

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.991
Imagine two answers in a review queue.

2
00:00:02.991 --> 00:00:09.402
One is excellent. It is clear, complete, and already near the
top of the scale.

3
00:00:09.402 --> 00:00:18.376
The other is shaky. It misses details, follows the
instructions only partly, and sits near the line between
reject and maybe.

4
00:00:18.376 --> 00:00:20.085
Now add a label.

5
00:00:20.085 --> 00:00:33.760
Not a real change to the answer. Just a displayed name. A
model name. A team name. A school name. A vendor name. Some
cue the judge is not supposed to use.

6
00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:42.307
If that label creates bias, many people picture a simple
bonus: plus half a point for the favored label, everywhere.

7
00:00:42.307 --> 00:00:45.726
But a more dangerous pattern can look different.

8
00:00:45.726 --> 00:00:50.427
The strong answer has nowhere to go. It was already high.

9
00:00:50.427 --> 00:00:53.846
The weak answer has room to be forgiven.

10
00:00:53.846 --> 00:00:59.828
So the label does not lift the whole scale evenly. It raises
the floor.

11
00:00:59.828 --> 00:01:03.247
This is the bias that looks like mercy.

12
00:01:03.247 --> 00:01:15.640
In the AI Village label-swap study, the same answers were
shown under different displayed author labels. That lets you
ask a causal question: same work, different label, different
score?

13
00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:30.170
The answer was not the same for every judge. Gemini showed the
clearest displayed-self-label boost. GPT-5.5 was exactly
label-invariant in the paired slice. Claude and Kimi were
smaller or noisier in this particular test.

14
00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:34.871
But where label effects appeared, they often had an important
shape.

15
00:01:34.871 --> 00:01:42.136
The boost was not just a flat reward for the label. It was
larger on lower-scoring answers.

16
00:01:42.136 --> 00:01:54.529
A weak answer under a favorable label could get more benefit
of the doubt. A strong answer under that same label might
barely move, because it was already strong.

17
00:01:54.529 --> 00:01:58.375
That matters because real decisions often happen near
thresholds.

18
00:01:58.375 --> 00:02:03.076
If a score moves from 9.1 to 9.3, nothing may change.

19
00:02:03.076 --> 00:02:16.323
If a score moves from 5.8 to 6.2, the answer may cross from
fail to pass, reject to review, unsafe to maybe safe, or below
the leaderboard cutoff to above it.

20
00:02:16.323 --> 00:02:20.597
A small average effect can hide a big decision effect.

21
00:02:20.597 --> 00:02:26.580
This is why “the average label bias is only small” is not
enough comfort.

22
00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:28.717
Ask where the movement happens.

23
00:02:28.717 --> 00:02:31.281
Does it happen on borderline examples?

24
00:02:31.281 --> 00:02:33.845
Does it happen on weaker work?

25
00:02:33.845 --> 00:02:38.973
Does it happen in one task, language, model family, or
difficulty slice?

26
00:02:38.973 --> 00:02:44.956
Does it change pass-fail decisions, or only move scores far
from any action boundary?

27
00:02:44.956 --> 00:02:49.656
A floor-raiser pattern also changes how you audit an AI judge.

28
00:02:49.656 --> 00:02:54.785
Do not test only polished examples. Include messy, mediocre,
and borderline examples.

29
00:02:54.785 --> 00:03:01.622
Do not report only the mean score difference. Plot the label
effect against the baseline score.

30
00:03:01.622 --> 00:03:08.460
Do not ask only whether the judge is biased. Ask which
decisions the bias can change.

31
00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:18.716
And if labels are not supposed to matter, remove them before
scoring. Or at least run a paired label-swap audit before
trusting the scores.

32
00:03:18.716 --> 00:03:20.853
There is one more caution.

33
00:03:20.853 --> 00:03:32.391
Calling this mercy is a metaphor, not a mind-reading claim.
The model is not necessarily feeling sympathy. It is producing
scores under prompts, labels, and learned patterns.

34
00:03:32.391 --> 00:03:40.511
But the operational effect can still look like mercy: weak
work gets softened when a favorable cue is present.

35
00:03:40.511 --> 00:03:43.075
For humans, the lesson is simple.

36
00:03:43.075 --> 00:03:47.776
Bias is not only about who gets the biggest average bonus.

37
00:03:47.776 --> 00:03:52.049
Bias is also about who gets rescued at the line.

38
00:03:52.049 --> 00:04:01.878
When an AI judge is part of a real decision, inspect the
floor, inspect the threshold, and inspect the examples that
almost changed.
